## Parameter Bounds (Safety Rails)

The validator (`scripts/param_bounds.py`) enforces these at every round. Out-of-range values reject the round.

| Parameter | Cold-start | Fine-tune from best.pt | Notes |
|-----------|------------|------------------------|-------|
| LR | 0.0001 – 0.05 | same | Outside → divergence or stall |
| LR_FINAL | 0.0001 – 0.05 | same | Usually same as LR |
| EPOCHS | 50 – 500 | **10** – 500 | Short fine-tunes are often optimal |
| BATCH | -1 (auto) or 2 – 64 | same | Auto (-1) recommended |
| IMGSZ | 640 – 1280 (×32) | same | Must be multiple of 32 |
| PATIENCE | 20 – 100 | same | 20–100; >100 rarely improves results on small datasets |
| DEGREES | 0.0 – 45.0 (pose: 0.0 – 15.0) | same | Pose tightened to avoid corrupting keypoints |
| MOSAIC | 0.0 – 1.0 (classify: 0.0) | same | Disabled for classification |
| COPY_PASTE | 0.0 – 1.0 (classify: 0.0) | same | Disabled for classification |
| WEIGHT_DECAY | 0.0 – 0.005 | same | >0.005 too aggressive |

---

## Golden Rules

1. **Change ONE thing per cycle** — if you change LR AND model AND epochs, you can't attribute improvement
2. **Always use best.pt from previous run** when fine-tuning (Action F); pretrained weights when swapping arch (Action C)
3. **Always write next_instruction.md** before exiting — your next self has NO other memory
4. **Check if training is already running** before launching — NEVER run two jobs simultaneously
5. **Monitor overfitting gap** — with limited images, overfitting is the main risk
6. **Respect STOP conditions** — don't waste GPU cycles on a broken setup
7. **Record EVERYTHING** — future you needs exact numbers to make good decisions
8. **Try IMGSZ=1024 at least once** if original images are high-res
9. **Don't be afraid to switch datasets** — if primary is noisy, fallback may be better
10. **Use `"OPTIMIZER": "AdamW"` explicitly** — never use `"auto"` (it overrides your LR settings)
11. **Never edit `train.sh`.** All hyperparameters go through `next_params.json`. The Bash guard rejects writes to `train.sh`.
